{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T16-35-42-620Z","slug":"are-promises-broken","locale":"it","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T16:36:06.773Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2018-10-06--are-promises-broken/index.md","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2018-10-06--are-promises-broken/it/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/are-promises-broken/it/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T16-35-42-620Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"7294bee00d55cef17088d7835790873a9b74a5ac4ecf3e4b97b76e98fa597095","outputHash":"65d8e74cd5f2736a7eb16b530b57fd0f9ace3bedd9a7c1b028114c1325654b4a","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary:**  \nThe article argues that JavaScript Promises are not inherently flawed but often misused due to lingering myths about their error-handling capabilities. It critiques outdated perceptions (e.g., errors being \"broken\") and highlights that modern Promises are robust, with fixes widely adopted. Key technical advice includes always returning values to maintain promise chains, using `Error` instances for meaningful stack traces, strategically placing `.catch()` to handle errors, and favoring named functions for readability. The tone is analytical and corrective, targeting JavaScript developers who may still rely on flawed practices or anti-patterns. Recurring metaphors include \"rules to stay out of trouble\" and framing Promises as tools requiring disciplined use rather than replacement (e.g., with `async/await`).","totalInputTokens":8943,"totalOutputTokens":8531,"totalCacheReadTokens":2048,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":19766,"totalCostUsd":0.00276288,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChunks":9,"totalInputTokens":8943,"totalOutputTokens":8531,"totalCacheReadTokens":2048,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":19766,"totalCostUsd":0.00276288,"prici